<font color="#FF0000">TELL YOUR STORY, VIET SON</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jun  5 21:41:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Viet Son, I might as well chime in with my two cents worth of opinion. I write both as a survivor, and a protestor. Of the latter I have said enough. Too many died, whether it was the will of Washington or Hanoi, Moscow or Bejing, I doubt that we will ever know the &quot;real&quot; truth. But the truth of death is all too clear. <br><br>
As to the former, I am a decendent, second generation, of immigrants, Jews. That gives me the unique perspective of living in, and being educated in, a country that draws its roots from Europe and Anglo-Saxons. Those roots also were the persistent slaughter and persecution of my people for the last 2000 years. Christian Europe, of which America draws its heritage, was the graveyard for my relatives, yet America is the savior for me and my relatives. (Go figure?)  <br><br>
Unfortunately, death and destruction knows no name, and knows no limits.  My unknown cousins, shoeless and coatless, shoveled snow in the Russian winter so the German troops could walk by, and helped build the railroad tracks as they starved to death, and then, if still alive, were loaded onto cattle cars to ultimately end up in ovens. Their gold teeth to be pulled out, melted down, and sold to Swiss Bankers. 450 Million dollars alone in gold teeth. The mind staggers at the numbers that equates too. <br><br>
Pol Pot and the other horrible monsters of war, are unfortunately, not a new invention.  The &quot;Viet Nam War&quot; was the death of many of your people. WW2 was the death of many of mine. I am the product of survival, and so shall you be, if you are not already.  Learn from the Jews, the Armenians, those that survived Holecausts of every type, learn that &quot;never again&quot; must be lived every day, EVERY DAY. Learn that hypocracy, whether it be preached on Sunday, or practiced on Monday, is alive and well, and must be confronted on every level at every chance.  <br><br>
As an Arabic proverb says: &quot;the enemy of my enemy is my friend&quot;, I choose to reword it to say: 'The bigot of your people today is the racist of my people tomorrow.'  Tell your story, Viet Son, but more importantly, never stop surviving, never stop telling others about it. The world's collective memory is far too short.<br><br>
Another problem is that victims survive to tell their stories, yet the &quot;perps&quot;, those that commit the foulest of deeds, from Hitler to Pol Pot, Swiss Banks to Joe Stalin, seem only to find real justice in the history books years later.   &quot;Never Again&quot; to you and yours, from me and mine.  We, the survivors, MUST, always, and continuing, tell our stories, to never let &quot;those who voiced their protest with their vote&quot; or their beer stein, to forget the horrors that were committed in their silent name.  <br><br>

